    <ProposalType>Science</ProposalType>
    <Title>Gotta catch’Em All: the spectroscopic follow-up of strong gravitational lenses from KiDS and KABS surveys</Title>
    <Abstract>Strong gravitational lenses are rare treasures yielding scientific insight into a large number of astrophysical and cosmological open questions, such as the expansion history of the Universe and the formation and evolution of massive galaxies and their dark matter haloes.
Progress in these fields is currently limited by the small number of known lenses, whether with extended sources (e.g., gravitational arcs) or compact sources (e.g., multiple images of lensed quasars). 
For this reason, we decided we "Gotta catch’Em All". We assembled a large team of experts with the goal of finding the largest possible number of new lenses, taking advantage of the improved image quality and the more extended and homogeneous sky coverage achieved with new, deep sky surveys, like KiDS and KABS. 
Using different techniques, from data mining to colour pre-selection and visual inspection, we have collected ~300 high-grade candidates. 
With this proposal, we aim to spectroscopically follow-up the 50 most promising systems, with the final goal of unambiguously confirming their lensing nature, and obtaining the redshifts of the sources and the deflectors.</Abstract>
