    <Outreach>
        <ns2:Summary>Gravitational lensing is an astrophysical phenomenon  predicted by Einstein's general relativity, which consists in the deflection of light by gravitational fields. If two galaxies are approximatively along the same line of sight, then the foreground galaxy (the lens) is bending the light of the background galaxy or quasar, generating arcs and multiple images. The gravitational lens is like a glass and the light of the background source is like the light of a candle, which seen through the bottom of the glass, appear as a series of distorted images and arcs. Gravitational lenses are not only spectacular events, but, are powerful tools to probe the mass distribution of the lens galaxies and constrain the age of the Universe. For these reasons, we are searching and finding new gravitational lenses, and we need to measure their spectra, i.e. the light they emit at different wavelengths, to determine how far are the lens and the background source. This is the first step to have a confirmation that our candidates are real lenses and proceed to more detailed analysis.</ns2:Summary>
